---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'FAQ | divorcesettlementcalc.com';
const description = 'Frequently asked questions about divorce settlements: community property, equitable distribution, spousal support, and retirement account division.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Frequently Asked Questions</h1>
  <h2>What is the difference between community property and equitable distribution?</h2>
  <p>Community property states (California, Texas, Arizona, and six others) presume that all property acquired during the marriage is owned 50/50. Equitable distribution states divide marital property &ldquo;fairly&rdquo; based on multiple factors &mdash; this does not mean equal. Outcomes in equitable distribution states vary more widely.</p>
  <h2>Is my spouse entitled to half my retirement account?</h2>
  <p>The portion of retirement benefits accrued during the marriage is generally marital property and subject to division. Division of 401(k)s and pensions requires a Qualified Domestic Relations Order (QDRO). The pre-marital portion and any post-separation contributions are typically separate property.</p>
  <h2>Does fault (adultery, etc.) affect the settlement?</h2>
  <p>In no-fault states (the vast majority now), fault has little or no effect on property division. In fault states, misconduct may affect alimony or, in some states, slightly shift property division &mdash; but the effect is usually modest.</p>
  <h2>What is a QDRO?</h2>
  <p>A Qualified Domestic Relations Order is a court order that directs a retirement plan administrator to pay a portion of one spouse&rsquo;s retirement benefits directly to the other spouse. It must comply with ERISA and the specific plan&rsquo;s requirements. Failing to obtain a QDRO can result in losing the awarded retirement share.</p>
  <h2>How long does spousal support last?</h2>
  <p>Varies by state and circumstance. Short marriages: typically no alimony or short-term rehabilitative support (1&ndash;3 years). Medium marriages (7&ndash;15 years): rehabilitative support for several years. Long marriages (15+ years) with significant income disparity: long-term or permanent alimony in many states.</p>
  <h2>Can I keep the house?</h2>
  <p>Yes, if you can afford to buy out your spouse&rsquo;s equity and qualify for a mortgage in your name alone. If not, the house is typically sold and equity divided, or one spouse receives the house in exchange for other assets of equal value.</p>
</BaseLayout>
